title: For Sale:  M1 Garand Service Match Rifle
postcontent: I believe this is an M1 Garand built for an Air Force service rifle team by AF armorers at Lackland AFB in the late 50's or early 60's, from conversations with CMP armorers at Anniston. I have no paperwork to support this however, so you be the judge. It's a June 1943 Springfield receiver by the serial number , although the receiver has been highly polished and black chromed at some point and only the serial number is legible. This was common practice among service team rifles. The barrel is an LMR 10-1953 , which gauges at TE 2 and ME 2, and has a great bore and tight chamber. The trigger group is 1943 vintage Springfield which has had a trigger job, very smooth trigger pull. The bolt is an H&R. The rear sight group is a complete National Match, standard front sight. The operating rod is an RA National Match. The stock is very good, glass bedded in the type II national match style, and the only markings are "LK" (Lackland AFB), and "AFPG" (Air Force Premium Grade). No import marks. Very few service team rifles remain, most were cut up during the Bill Clinton era. Located in Carbon Hill, Alabama. Additional pictures available. $1600.00 or make offer. Might trade for a quality 308 battle rifle (M1A,M14,FAL), GI M1 Carbine, another Garand,or high end AR15.

The .22lr “Kalashnikov” manufactured by GSG represents much more than a small caliber “knock-off” of a famous rifle. The GSG-AK47 is not only a well-made rifle, common of the German engineering we have come to appreciate, but it actually bears the name “Kalashnikov.” GSG is currently the only company in the entire world licensed by Mr. Kalashnikov to manufacture real, functioning firearms, and they have not taken this opportunity lightly. The low cost of shooting .22lr ammo is attractive, but not really at the expense of an unfamiliar rifle with awkward controls and an uncertain reliability aspect. Fortunately for those who of us who like military rifles, all these issues were not a factor with the GSG-AK47. The look, feel and controls are almost identical to the most heavily proliferated rifle system in the world. Whether it is for los-cost training on the real system, a departure from the usual noise to give your neighbors a break, to help a youngster learn to handle this style rifle without the recoil and intimidation of the muzzle blast or just plain for fun, we think the GSG-AK47 will make a nice addition to any military firearms collection - See more at: http://www.americantactical.us/589/detail.html#sthash.ze1W6oZM.dpuf
